\noindent
We evaluate the pipeline on the pool of \emph{surviving} candidates produced by the search. For each target, the closed loop runs four objective branches (CLIP, LPIPS, MSE, and the composite), and within each branch it keeps every candidate that was actually rendered and scored, discarding only exact prompt repeats and renders that collapse to a duplicate image under the dHash check. The survivors of the four branches are pooled per image and then across all six targets, and each candidate is scored on the three metrics. Aggregated over the five optimiser seeds with the render seed held fixed, this yields $\NCAND$ scored candidates in total, the population over which the aggregate statistics below are computed and from which each target's top-3 is selected.

\subsection{Seeds and sampling temperature}
It is worth separating the two distinct sources of randomness in the pipeline, because they are handled in opposite ways.

\paragraph{\normalfont\textbf{Two kinds of seed.}} The first is the LCM \emph{render} seed, which controls the generator's own noise. It is fixed per image from the filename (for example \texttt{7836.png} renders with seed $7836$) and never changes, for any prompt, at any iteration, in any repetition of the experiment. This is what makes the generator deterministic, so that the same prompt always produces the same image and the metrics are a clean function of the prompt. The second is the \emph{optimiser} seed, which controls Qwen's stochastic prompt sampling. A global value (\texttt{set\_seed(1234)}) is set at start-up, but each individual proposal call also derives its own seed as \texttt{GEN\_SEED} plus a hash of the tuple (image, branch, iteration, call number). This keeps every call reproducible while making them mutually distinct: different branches and iterations do not replay the same sampling trajectory. Folding the iteration index into the seed is deliberate, since without it a new iteration would repeat the previous iteration's exact samples against a larger avoid-list, so every proposal would already be banned and the branch would collapse to zero new prompts. The optimiser seed is overridable from the environment, so the protocol's multi-seed sweep ($\ge 5$ repetitions) can vary the prompt search while the render seed stays fixed.

\paragraph{\normalfont\textbf{Temperature.}} Temperature applies only to Qwen; it does not touch the renderer, whose randomness is already pinned by the render seed (guidance scale and step count are constant). Proposals are sampled at a base temperature of $0.8$ with nucleus sampling (top-$p$ $0.95$), which gives varied but on-target wordings. When a proposal call returns nothing new, the temperature is escalated by $0.15$ per consecutive stale call up to a ceiling of $1.20$, flattening a peaked distribution until fresh wordings appear, and it drops back to the base once new prompts are found. A mild repetition penalty ($1.2$) further discourages the model from copying its own earlier output within a single call. The escalation only ever raises diversity: any malformed or off-target prompt that slips through at high temperature simply scores worse and is discarded during selection.

\section{Analysis of the Results}
\label{sec:results}

\subsection{Aggregate metrics across the test set}
Table~\ref{tab:aggregate} reports the mean$\pm$std of the three main metrics at three levels of aggregation: over \emph{all} rendered candidates, over the single \emph{best} candidate per image (top-1), and over the \emph{submitted top-3}.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Aggregate image-side metrics for the closed-loop method (mean$\pm$std). CLIP higher is better; LPIPS and pixel MSE lower is better.}
\label{tab:aggregate}
\small
\begin{tabular}{l c c c}
\toprule
\textbf{Aggregation} & \textbf{CLIP\,$\uparrow$} & \textbf{LPIPS\,$\downarrow$} & \textbf{Pixel MSE\,$\downarrow$} \\
\midrule
All candidates ($n{=}\NCAND$) & $0.816\pm0.053$ & $0.634\pm0.051$ & $0.0402\pm0.0116$ \\
Best per image ($n{=}6$)  & $\mathbf{0.849\pm0.072}$ & $\mathbf{0.583\pm0.076}$ & $\mathbf{0.0288\pm0.0110}$ \\
Submitted top-3 ($n{=}16$) & $0.844\pm0.064$ & $0.611\pm0.075$ & $0.0343\pm0.0147$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\noindent
The best reconstruction per image is strong on all three metrics simultaneously (CLIP $0.849$, LPIPS $0.583$, pixel MSE $0.0288$), which is the payoff of the closed loop: by rendering and scoring at every iteration, the search can fix the specific error of the current best candidate rather than hoping a blind sample lands well. The full candidate pool is also tight (std $\le 0.05$ on CLIP and LPIPS), because the search concentrates around the leading prompt instead of scattering independent samples. The gap between the best-per-image row and the submitted-top-3 row is explained in Section~\ref{sec:limits}: on several images the loop could not supply three genuinely \emph{distinct} strong survivors, so ranks~2--3 are weaker than rank~1 (and one image yields only a single candidate), which pulls the top-3 average down.

